Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, he was the third to vote on a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" won 28%, 7% of the votes were invalid and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls carried out at the exit of polling stations and a count by a non-governmental organization had announced a large victory of the "yes", between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on the night of Sunday to Monday.
The "Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly," he assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians at the headquarters of Guayaquil governorate, 280 kilometres south-west of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which took place calmly according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), concerned a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the State over the economy, reserving to it the "planning of the development" of a country living mainly from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currencies sent by its emigrants.
Carried out by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants strengthened powers to the Head of State, who will be able to carry out up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services which the President has begun to establish in that country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back this Monday afternoon safe and sound to the Egyptian capital.
In the morning, they had been released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived at about 3:30 p.m. on a special plane at al-Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, aboard helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examination.
They are in "good health", and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers," said Egyptian Minister of Tourism Zoheir Garanna on the tarmac.
Captured on 19 September during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the edge of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been flogged from one hideout to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptous, organiser of the safari.
An Egyptian security official reported that 30 members of the special forces, transported on board two helicopters, had launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of gunshots occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fled," said the official who demanded anonymity.
He reported that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "flash" unit had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men in the secret services, the special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The previous day, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle in which the kidnappers were on patrol, killing in six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army claimed that they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
