Benelux governments nationalize part of Bank Fortis
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Holland bank, as the first European bank in distress as a result of the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partly nationalising it. The three countries support, to the sum of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution also owns interest in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, in this case, also involving the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has been growing for more than a year is for Bank Fortis. From a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy almost half (up to 49%) of the bank's capital in each of the countries.
The bank will, without any doubt, sell a portion of its holdings, among which, first of all, the activities, mainly insurance, which it acquired last year from the Dutch agency ABN Amro.
Last week, the Fortis shares began a dizzying fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to let it go to bankruptcy.
On Friday alone, the company's shares dropped by 12 percent, to its lowest level 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two thirds of their value.
Taking into account the present value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around €14 billion, which, according to the company's management, is unrealistic.
The company's management is uncertain, in relation to the adoption of the $700 billion U.S. rescue plan, that it was responsible for the fall of Fortis shares.
On Monday, there has already been a slight increase in the number of papers.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new managing director.
The financial agency was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the substance.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank's customer circle and no agency was stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent agencies and has also bought leasing companies.
A fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about his purchases of medicines.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes that link the use of prescription information in all cases to the consent of the data subject.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting its henhouse to a fox" - recalled Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage medication prescriptions, at the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the capital insured in the event of damage, depend on the health of the client who comes forward, and if they think the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent the candidates for a medical examination, and they only signed an insurance contract with them after they became aware of the results.
For ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily obtains data from pharmacies on the person's purchases of medicines within the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, what disease the person suffers and what is his state of health.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts him in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is no longer much left for the insurer to do except for paperwork. However, tiny problems may still arise.
Disadvantages of this program include the fact that a drug can be used for a variety of purposes. For example, some mixtures may be used against migraine or hot flushes, but may also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of the data, and they must apply to the patient for authorisation before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their failures in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory analyses and linking them with data on drug use, and in this way they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health.
More and more companies have access to data, and control of usage is becoming more and more difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A proposal for a law on the enlargement of the control circle of the authorities concerning companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his programme, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive consent of the data subject.
It is also a question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her consent or not, since if he or she refuses, the insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
So and ultimately, the hens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other, largely global, issues.
Today, a France-India summit will also be held, focusing on cooperation in the field of atomic energy.
The European Union recognizes that India is a great emerging democratic power that should be given a wider right to speak in international affairs, but member countries have not yet managed to agree on their support in New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not dwell too much on this issue yesterday at the 9th summit held in Marseilles.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, like the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years they would double trade, meaning an increase of about 100 billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be an overly ambitious objective.
In this sense, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral agreements with India on civil flights, and in this way air trade will also be able to expand in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, the EU's leading trading partner, on the one hand, and New Delhi, on the other, which is only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit devoted its attention to global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan had been strongly condemned, as had all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on that subject had been raised.
The completion of the Doha trade round has also been called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains committed to the energy and climate agenda, in particular that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic materials by at least 20 per cent until 2020.
India also agreed on this, as well as with the need for a global market at next year's climate conference, and to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by fifty per cent until 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian Head of State is now travelling to the French capital, where during a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to the news agency's information, the agreement would cover 15 years.
